Base.Explanation: Searches the Active Directory for one or more objects. For each object found, the object distinguished name is returned. For the search, you need to specify the environment (LDAP, GC, domain, ou, etc.) and the LDAP search string.

ArrayElement.Name: Search environment
ArrayElement.Description: The search is performed in one of three possible environment: LDAP, GC or any other object. To search the entire Active Directory environment accessible from the local computer, specify the word LDAP (1). To search in the Global Catalog, specify the word GC (2). To search in any other environment, specify the LDAP binding string to access the object (3). Example: To search in a specify domain: LDAP://domain or LDAP://host. To search in a specific OU: LDAP://domaincontroller/OU=students,DC=domain,DC=com.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP search Filter
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP search filter according to RFC 2254. Example, to find user accounts with a specific description field 1234: (&(objectClass=user) (&(description=1234))

ArrayElement.Name: Error if nothing found
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if no matching objects are found.

ArrayElement.Name: Error if multiple found
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if multiple matching objects are found.

ArrayElement.Name: Search in child objects
ArrayElement.Description: Search in the specified environment and child objects, for example child domains.

ArrayElement.Name: Number of objects found
ArrayElement.Description: The number of matching objects found. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. By default, the value for this property is stored in variable %SearchResultCount%.

ArrayElement.Name: Object distinguished names
ArrayElement.Description: The distinguished names of the matching objects. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. By default, the value for this property is stored in variable %SearchResults%.

Base.Explanation: Access a user account in Active Directory. The action is used always in combination with other subsequent actions. Once the user is found, an internal data structure representing the user account is is setup. This structure is stored in a variable (%UserObject%) that can be used by other actions. The action supports several methods to find the user.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the domain (DNS or NETBIOS style, e.g. tools4ever.com or TOOLS4EVER) of the user account. The user account is specified using LDAP. To specify the user account, you have three options. 1: LDAP name (available from network tree browse operations), 2: Domain + Organizational Unit-Container + FullName (the LDAP name is composed from the individual components), 3: Domain + Username (NT-style, LDAP name is searched for). For each option, you need to specify the corresponding properties.

ArrayElement.Name: Organizational Unit-Container
ArrayElement.Description: The name of the Organizational Unit-Container of the user account (example: Students or Students\Group1). The user account is specified using LDAP. To specify the user account, you have three options. 1: LDAP name (available from network tree browse operations), 2: Domain + Organizational Unit-Container + FullName (the LDAP name is composed from the individual components), 3: Domain + Username (NT-style, LDAP name is searched for). For each option, you need to specify the corresponding properties.

ArrayElement.Name: Full name
ArrayElement.Description: The full name, more precisely known as the common name of the user account in the Organizational Unit-Container - Domain (example: John Williams). The user account is specified using LDAP. To specify the user account, you have three options. 1: LDAP name (available from network tree browse operations), 2: Domain + Organizational Unit-Container + FullName (the LDAP name is composed from the individual components), 3: Domain + Username (NT-style, LDAP name is searched for). For each option, you need to specify the corresponding properties.

ArrayElement.Name: Username
ArrayElement.Description: The pre-Windows 2000 logon name of the user account (example: JWilliams). The user account is specified using LDAP. To specify the user account, you have three options. 1: LDAP name (available from network tree browse operations), 2: Domain + Organizational Unit-Container + FullName (the LDAP name is composed from the individual components), 3: Domain + Username (NT-style, LDAP name is searched for). For each option, you need to specify the corresponding properties.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP name
ArrayElement.Description: The full LDAP name of the user account. (example: cn=John Williams, ou=Schools, dc=Tools4ever, dc=Com). If this value is specified, it takes precendece and the values for the properties 'Domain', 'Organizational Unit-Container', 'Full name' and 'Username' are ignored and do not have to be specified.

ArrayElement.Name: Domain controller
ArrayElement.Description: Optional: The name of the domain controller, used to access to the domain, container or organizational unit where the account exists. This property can be used for any of the methods used to specify the user account. If this value is not specified, Active Directory chooses one automatically (serverless binding).

ArrayElement.Name: User Object
ArrayElement.Description: An internal data structure representing the user account. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated automatically when the user is found in Active Directory. This property can be used in other script actions, for instance to create an Exchange mailbox, setup group memberships or modify user attributes.

ArrayElement.Name: User Security Identifier (SID)
ArrayElement.Description: The security identifier (SID) of the user account. This property is an 'output only' property and can be determined when the user is found in Active Directory. The 'User Security Identifier' (SID) is created by the Active Directory automatically when the user account was created. The SID is used when setting permissions, for instance on home directories, Exchange mailboxes etc. The SID is stored by default in the variable %UserSid%.

ArrayElement.Name: Globally unique identifier (GUID)
ArrayElement.Description: The globally unique identifier (GUID) of the user account. This property is an 'output only' property and can be determined when the user is found in Active Directory. The 'User Security Identifier' (SID) is created by the Active Directory automatically when the user account was created. The SID is used when setting permissions, for instance on home directories, Exchange mailboxes etc. The SID is stored by default in the variable %UserGuid%.

ArrayElement.Name: User account display name
ArrayElement.Description: The display name of the user account. This property is an 'output only' property and can be determined when the user is found in Active Directory.

Base.Explanation: Get the value of an attribute of an Active Directory object, for instance a user account. The attribute is specified by the LDAP display name of the attribute. For the most common properties, the LDAP name can be selected from a list.

ArrayElement.Name: User Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing a user account. If you want to obtain the property of a user account object, you can use this property to specify the Active Directory object for this action. Use the action 'Get user (AD)' to find the user account in Active Directory and setup the variable that contains the 'User Object'.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing a Active Directory object for which an attribute must obtained. This property can only be used as a input variable. Earlier in the script, another script action must have generated the value for this variable.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP attribute display name
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP name of the attribute. The name identifies the attribute of the Active Directory object. For a number of well-known attributes, the LDAP name can be selected from a list but you can specify any other valid name.

ArrayElement.Name: Multi-value flag
ArrayElement.Description: Save multi-values as multi-values for the attribute. If set to 'Yes' and the attribute is multi-valued, the values are stored as multi-values (text list or table). If set to 'No' and the attribute is multi-valued, the values are converted into a single value. Default value: 'No'.

ArrayElement.Name: Convert to text flag
ArrayElement.Description: Convert the value(s) of the attribute to text. Default value: 'Yes'. If set, depending on property 'Multi-value flag', the result is either a single text or text list. If not set ('No'), the results is stored as one of the UMRA supported data types.

ArrayElement.Name: Error if no attribute found
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if the specified attribute is not found.

ArrayElement.Name: Error if empty
ArrayElement.Description: Generate an error for this script action if the attribute is found but attribute value is empty.

ArrayElement.Name: Attribute value
ArrayElement.Description: The value found for the attribute. This property is an 'output only' property and is generated by the application automatically. By default, the value for this property is stored in variable %AttributeValue%.

ArrayElement.MailSubject: Nieuwe medewerker uit AFAS gekomen, geen manager gevonden: %cellvalue4% %cellvalue5% %cellvalue6%
ArrayElement.MailMessage:
Hi Marco,
Een nieuwe medewerker (%cellvalue4% %cellvalue5% %cellvalue6%) is in de UMRA database gezet, vanuit Profit. Normaliter gaat er dan een e-mail naar de manager(s). Dit is nu niet mogelijk. Umra heeft geen managers gevonden.
Groet, UMRA Mailservice
